\significancestatement{
Colleges and universities often make announcements about increases in the diversity of tenure-track faculty, but are those changes keeping pace with changes in the population? In this analysis of every higher education institution in the U.S., we find that at current rates of change, faculty diversity in the U.S. will never reach parity with the general population. Institutions sometimes argue that these patterns are caused by a lack of qualified candidates. Using national data on earned doctorates, we show evidence of tens of thousands of qualified, eligible candidates. While higher education needs to increase the rate of change by 3.5 times to reach demographic parity by 2050, our analyses suggest there is an ample supply of faculty of color to meet the demand.
