\begin{abstract}
Colleges and universities across the U.S. have publicized commitments to recruit and retain faculty of color, reporting increases in the percentage of faculty from under-represented groups. Yet individual trends may not always reflect sector-wide changes. Are U.S. higher education and groups of peer institutions making progress toward demographic parity or falling behind? And to what degree are these patterns bounded by a ``leak in the pipeline'' of qualified applicants? In this paper, we model changes over time in tenure-track faculty diversity for every higher education institution in the US and their peer institutions. We find that at current rates of change, faculty diversity in the U.S. will never reach demographic parity with the general population. To achieve racial parity by 2050, colleges and universities will need to diversify their faculty at 3.5 times the current pace. Is this change achievable given the supply of eligible PhDS? To test the pipeline hypothesis, we analyzed data from the National Survey of Earned Doctorates, finding that between 2007 and 2019, over 45,000 newly minted PhDs from underrepresented racial groups were not hired into tenure-track positions. These findings provide evidence that the pipeline for a racially diverse faculty is plentiful, and that colleges and universities in the US must restructure and re-pace their recruitment and retention efforts to achieve their goals of racial equity and diversity among their faculty.

\end{abstract}

