\dropcap{U}S colleges and universities have spent at least a decade bemoaning the lack of racial diversity in their institutions. Part of their angst about the state of their institutions has come from external pressure. For example, in 2012, the President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology noted that it was a strategic necessity for the U.S. to increase the size of its scientific workforce, and diversity in that workforce \cite{holdren_engage_2012}. But it is not just the government that has called for greater diversity in the academic labor market, universities themselves have declared diversity, equity, and inclusion to be central to their missions and have made pledges to increase faculty diversity (Lewis, 2022). Despite all of the ink that has been spilled on this topic, universities seem to have little results to show for their ostensible efforts \cite{matias_universities_2021}. Indeed, ten years later, the current President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology are making essentially the same call to action that their predecessors made a decade, and two presidential administrations, ago. 

Why have universities made such little progress? One common refrain is that there is simply a "pipeline problem"--there are too few students of color (and in some fields, too few women) available to fill in the faculty ranks as positions open up. If there are not enough students on the pathway to the professoriate, then there is simply nothing universities can do; they would have to continue the practice of hiring primarily white and male faculty to fill their faculty ranks. If there is diversity in the pipeline, however, then the common refrain would not be a sufficient explanation for the lack of progress in diversifying American colleges and universities. 

In the current paper, we examine whether the pipeline hypothesis is a sufficient explanation for the lack of diversity in American universities by combining three comprehensive national data sets to build models of faculty diversity, and projections of how diversity might (or might not change) in the future. First, we model the changes in faculty diversity from 2013 to 2021 for all of higher education, institution groups, and individual institutions. Second, we use U.S. Census projections to examine whether faculty composition is changing at rates that are making higher education more diverse, or whether interventions might be necessary to move the faculty diversity trajectory closer to broader demographic parity. Finally, we estimate the number of qualified underrepresented minority faculty that are available for universities to hire if they chose to. If there is diversity in the pipeline, then the common refrain would not be a sufficient explanation of the lack of progress in diversifying college in the US. Indeed, higher education would then need to consider other institutional barriers and solutions towards its diversity goals (Griffin, 2020).

