\section*{Results}

We find that the diversity of tenure-track faculty in the U.S. is not increasing any faster than the diversity of the American public. In a linear regression model across \Sexpr{prettyNum(nrow(subset(institution.models.df, dv==dv.var)),big.mark="," )} higher education institutions, the percentage of under-represented tenure-track faculty increased by \Sexpr{prettyNum(coef(summary(linear.m1))['year.zeroed',][['Estimate']]*100, digits=2)} percentage points each year on average between the 2013 and 2020 academic years (p<0.0001,$R^2 = \Sexpr{prettyNum(summary(linear.m1)$r.squared, digits=2)}$). During that period and into the future, the U.S. Census protects that the percentage of demographic groups under-represented among faculty will increase by 0.2 percentage points per year. At this rate, U.S. higher education will never achieve demographic parity among tenure-track faculty (Figure \ref{fig:urm-faculty}: All).

Despite variation in rates of change between institutions, these sector-wide  patterns are similar between peer groups. Among Ivy+ Institutions, for instance, the percentage of under-represented tenure-track faculty increased by \Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(ivyplus.models.df, subgroup_value=="True" & dv=="tenured_un_tenured_black_latino_american_indian_alaska_native_hawaiian_pacific_multiracial_total_pct")$year_estimate*100, digits=2)} percentage points per year (p<0.0001). Across R1 universities, the percentage increased by \Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(carnegie.models.df, subgroup_value==15 & dv=="tenured_un_tenured_black_latino_american_indian_alaska_native_hawaiian_pacific_multiracial_total_pct")$year_estimate*100, digits=2)}  per year (p<0.0001). Among National Liberal Arts Colleges, the percentage increased by \Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(usnews.models.df, subgroup_value=='National Liberal Arts Colleges' & dv=="tenured_un_tenured_black_latino_american_indian_alaska_native_hawaiian_pacific_multiracial_total_pct")$year_estimate*100, digits=2)} percentage points per year (p=\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(usnews.models.df, subgroup_value=='National Liberal Arts Colleges' & dv=="tenured_un_tenured_black_latino_american_indian_alaska_native_hawaiian_pacific_multiracial_total_pct")$year_pvalue, digits=1)}), faster than the rate of change in the population. Due to this higher rate of change, the percentage of under-represented tenure-track faculty at National Liberal Arts Colleges in 2060 will only be \Sexpr{prettyNum(nla.prop.diff*100, digits=2)} percentage points behind the general population, compared to a gap of \Sexpr{prettyNum(us.prop.diff*100, digits=2)} percentage points across all institutions.

How can U.S. higher education achieve demographic parity among tenure-track faculty within the next three decades (i.e., within our lifetime)? We estimate that the sector could achieve demographic parity by 2050 by collectively increasing under-represented faculty by one percentage point per year overall---an increase of \Sexpr{prettyNum(rate.increase.2050*100, digits=2)} percentage points on the current rate of change.

Conversations about faculty diversity often invoke a ``leaky pipeline,'' despite conflicting empirical evidence \cite{gibbs_jr_decoupling_2016, griffin_institutional_2019}. If higher education as a sector committed to demographic parity by 2050, would they have access to qualified candidates? To investigate this question, we estimate the cumulative number of U.S. citizens from under-represented groups who have received PhDs since 2007 and who have not yet been hired into tenure-track faculty positions. Between 2007 and the 2019 job market year, U.S. higher education granted \Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(merged.df, year==2020)$cumulative_unhired_prev_year, big.mark=",")} PhDs to people from under-represented groups who were not hired into tenure-track positions (Figure \ref{fig:unhired}). This cumulative sum of un-hired PhDs is equivalent to \Sexpr{prettyNum((subset(merged.df, year==2020)$cumulative_unhired_prev_year / subset(year.df, year==2020)$tenured_un_tenured_Grand_total_sum)*100, digits=4)} percent of all tenure-track faculty in the United States in 2020.


